3) So I might want to build a model with Poisson distribution in each loop of data, since the density is the highest at around counts of five and spread out to both sides. As we see the mean value in the Poisson model approaching 5 as in the data, however, it barely reflects the abundance of other detection with higher mean particle counts. But just based on the amount of data of particles counts, we can say the particles counts may follow a Poisson distribution. And then, the average particle count approaches to the mean as time evolves, saying that the time dependence must follow another model that has a increasing distribution, which can be combined with the model of particle counts to reach a similar background distribution.

In [27]:
mu = 5
s = 10000
time_model = np.linspace(9.40684, 9.40689, s)

counts_model = stats.poisson.rvs(mu, loc = 0, size = s)
b = (45,15) 

plt.hist2d(time_model, counts_model, bins=b, density=True)
plt.ylabel("counts", fontsize = 18)
plt.xlabel("time", fontsize = 18)
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

pts = np.arange(stats.poisson.ppf(0.00001, 5), stats.poisson.ppf(.99999, 5))
plt.plot(pts, stats.poisson.pmf(pts, 5), 'bo', ms=10, label='poisson pmf')
plt.vlines(pts, 0, stats.poisson.pmf(pts, 5), colors='b', lw=5, alpha=0.5)
plt.show()

4) The calculated 5-sigma is 18, and based on the graph, the discover threshold falls beyond the bright point at about 14 particle counts in each period of oscillation.
